{"/service/ndnp/ct/batch_ct_grasso_ver02/data/sn82014085/00393346966/1937111501/0241.xml":{"full_text":"resident Asks For\nCooperation Of All\n(Continued from Pace 1)\nRegarding raxes, kit.\nwarned against action so quick and\nsweeping as to create budgetary dif\nficulties and Inequities.\n\"Modifications adequate to en\ncourage productive enterprise, es\npecially for the smaller businesses,\nmust not extend to the point of\nusing the corporate form for the\npurpose of hiding behind It to re\nduce or eliminate taxes In a way not\nopen to an Individual or partner\nship,\" he said.\n\u2022'Nor,\u201d said Mr. Roosevelt, \"should\nWe extend tax privileges to specula\ntive profits on capital where the in\ntent of the original risk was specu\nlation rather than the actual devel\nopment of productive enterprise.\nRevision of Revenue Laws\n\"Nor can we at this time accept a\nrevision of our revenue laws which\ninvolves a reduction In the aggre\ngate revenues or an Increase In the\naggregate tax burdens of those least\nable to bear them.\"\nMr. Roosevelt cautioned congress\nand the nation against regarding\nthe business recession as akin to\nthat of 1929.\n\"With the exercise of ordinary\nprudence,\u201d he said, \"there Is no rea\nson why we should suffer any pro\nlonged recession, let alone any gen\neral economic paralysis. Despite\nsome maladjustments, which can be\ncorrected, underlying conditions are\nnot unfavorable.\nxne lunaamcniai situation is not\nto be compared with the far differ\nent conditions of 1929. The banking\nsystem Is not over-extended. Inter\nest rates are lower. Inventories are\nnot dangerously large. We are no\nlonger over-extended In new con\nstruction or in capital equipment.\nSpeculation requiring liquidation\ndoes not over hang our markets.\u201d\nMr. Roosevelt warned that if pri\nvate enterprise did not take up the\nslaok in unemployment, the govern\nment would be forced to intervene.\n\u201cThe ultimate answer to the con\nditions of today,\u201d he declared, \"is a\ncordial and confident cooperation\nnot only between government and\nevery kind of citizen\u2014but also be\ntween every kind of citizen and his\ngovernment.\u201d\nMr. Roosevelt did not read his\nmessage to congress in person. How\never, prior to convocation of the\nHouse and Senate at noon, he called\nhis chief legislative lieutenants to\nthe White House and there, in his\noval blue and white office in the\nexecutive wing of the mansion, read\nhis recommendations to them.\nCovered Four Subjects\nMT. Roosevelt's message covered\nonly four of the five legislative sub\njects mentioned when he summoned\nCongress to convene in special ses\nsion. He submitted no recommenda\ntion for revision of anti-trust laws\nbut did point to Ihe need for inquiry\ninto the anti-trust situation. He in\ndicated that he would present fur\nther recommendations to Congress\nat various intervals.\nSit asking Congress to enact farm\ncontrol legislation, Mr. Roosevelt re\niterated that if expenditures are au\nthorized beyond those provided for\nin the regular budget, taxes must be\nlevied to meet the added costs. He\nsuggested that the Wagner Labor Act\nand Social Security decisions of the\nsupreme court gave hope that, de\nspite invalidation of the AAA, Con\ngress would enact \u201can adequate farm\nact.\u201d\nWages, Hours\nRegarding wages and hours, Mr.\nRoosevelt declared he did not have\nIn mind Immediate enactment ol\nuniform minimum wages and hours\nstandards.\n\"That Is the ultimate goal,\u201d he\nsaid. \"We should provide flexible\nmachinery which will enable Indus\ntries throughout the country to ad\njust themselves progressively to bet\nter labor conditions.\"\nHis principal objectives he de\nscribed as elimination of child la\nbor, protection oi workers against\nexcessively long hours and low\nwages, and a safeguard against the\n\u201cunsound practice of some commu\nnities\u201d which seek to attract new in\ndustries solely because labor is cheap\ner than in competing communities.\nReorganization Flan\nHe appealed for enactment of his\ngovernment reorganization program\non a basis of efficiency. He took issue\nhowever, with those who suggested\nlarge savings might come from reor\nganization, asserting that such sav\nings could only come through elimi\nnation of government functions.\nHe declared that his regional plan\nning recommendations would decen\ntralize and make more efficient the\nspending of government funds for\nnational resources improvement.\n\u201cWhat these four subjects promise\nIn continued and increased purchas\ning power\u2014what they promise in\ngreater efficiency in the use of gov\nernment funds\u2014are intelligent foun\ndations for the other plans for en\ncouragement of industrial expansion:\nwith government help,\u201d said the\npresident. \u201cWhat they promise in so\ncial contentment is an almost neces\nsary basis for greater security ol\nprofits and property.\nDiscussed Everywhere\n\u201cIn the months they have been\nbefore the Congress they have been\ndiscussed from one end of the coun\ntry to the other.\n\u201cFor the sake of the nation, I hope\nfor your early action.\"\nThis is the second special session\nsince Mr. Roosevelt took office. De\nspite his plea for action, the fore\ncast in many quarters was for much\ntalk and little achievement this ses\nsion.\nSession Opens\nWashington, Nov. 15\u2014(UP)\u2014The\n15th Congress convened in special\nsession at 12:01 p. m. today. The\nhouse was called to order at noon\nand the senate quickly followed.\nThe first order of business was the\nreading of the presidential procla\nmation summoning congress to meet.\nThe senate floor resembled a\nnone-too-sedate club room as sena\ntors reassembled, many of them in\nmorning coats and striped trousers.\nA roar of chatter rose from the\nfloor as members worked their way\nbaolc and forth between the desks,\nshaking hands and clapping each\nother on the back.\nBen. Hattie Caraway, d\u201e Ark., with\na berlbboned corsage of orchids on\nher shoulder lent the single splash\nof color to the somber scene. Sen.\nDixie Bibbs Grave, d., Ala., wore a\nplain black dress with silver orna\nments.\nThe buzz of conversations contin\nued in a subdued tone after the Rev.\nBamey T. Philips said prayer and\nwhile the clerk read the call for the\nipecial session.\nSen. Caraway presented creden\nLUals of newly-elected Sen. John E.\nmmct) u.) ntn. vice ricoiucub uutui\nN. Garner swore him In.\nAfter the special session call was\nread in the house a roll call was\nbegun.\nMore than 300 of the 435 members\nwere In their seats.\nThe senate recessed at 13:15 p. m.\nuntil 1:30 to notify the president\nthat it is in session.\nGarner appointed Barkley and\nMcNary as members of a Joint com\nmittee to notify the president.\nNeither house is prepared to pro\nceed at once with the major legis\nlation dealing with agriculture and\nlabor..\nFuture Is Beclouded\nDivision of the New Deal Demo\ncratic party assurance of a fat\ndeficit this year and a business re\ncession becloud the legislative fu\nture. Mr. Roosevelt\u2019s leadership was\nchallenged and defeated on vital is\nsues last session.\nCongressional tempers are still\nhot. A conservative bloc of senate\nDemocrats Including Senator Pat\nHarrison, Miss., and Senator Carter\nGlass, Va., may challenge Mr.\nRoosevelt again to seek modifica\ntion of the new deal, and easing\nof tax burdens on business and\nfinance, and real economy to bal\nance the budget.\nLegislators summoned by Mr.\nRoosevelt to further the more\nabundant life with key bills framed\nIn behalf of agriculture, labor and\nsmall business are faced suddenly\nwith tremendous pressure to legis\nlate in behalf of business and\nfinance, and especially to modify\nnew deal tax laws.\nChallenge To Proponals\nSlumping business, an unexpect\nly bad treasury situation and stock\nmarket weakness hauntingly like\nthat of 1929 combine to challenge\nclaims of agriculture and labor up\non congress this time. Federal reve\nnue has fallen consistently below\nestimates in this fiscal year. Deficit\nestimates have risen accordingly.\nBusiness protests it almost is ham\nstrung by new deal levies <m capi\ntal gains and upon corporation in\ncome which is placed in reserve in\nstead of being distributed as divi\ndends.\nThere arc indications as congress\nmeets of willingness to go a little\nway toward easing these strictures\nand a coincident movement in both\nthe executive and legislative\nbranches of government to do some\nthing about the series of treasury\ndeficits under which the national\ndebt was swollen to $37,000,000,000.\nTax Revision Delayed\nLeaders apparently are agreed\nthat tax revision must wait until\nthe rjgular session beginning in\nJanuary. One or two of Mr. Roose\nvelt's special session bills may\nsqueeze through, but there is no as\nsurance of that. The senate is rip\nped already by dispute over the\nanti-lynching bill which must be\nfaced this autumn and there is\nprospect of a first class filibuster by\nsouthern senators against it. That\nalone might snarl Congress so that\nnothing could be accomplished un\ntil 1938.\ninis is tne second session oi me\n75th congress which was elected In\nNovember 1936 In the Roosevelt\nsweep which gave the new deal\nevery state except Maine and Ver\nmont. The first session convened in\nJanuary 1936. It rebelled against Mr.\nRoosevelt's Judiciary reorganization\nbill and finally beat it after eight\nmonths of bitter debate.\nThat debate and developments\naround it divided the Democratic\nparty in congress and created a po\ntential conservative Democratic\nleadership on Capitol Hill which\nmay be able to challenge the presi\ndent in this session and the next.\nShowdown In Expenditures\nA showdown is coming on govern\nment expenditures. Secretary of\nTreasury Henry Morgenthau, Jr.,\nlast week proposed that the budget\nbe balanced next year by trimming\n$700,000,000 from the current $3,\n311,000,000 appropriations for unem\nployment relief, civilian conservation\ncorps, highways, public works and\nagriculture. The national reaction to\nMorgenthau's plan was favorable.\nChairman Pat Harrison of the sen\nate finance committee and other\ninfluential conservative Democrats\npublicly endorsed painful economy.\nBut the first concrete related devel\nopment was consideration by a\nhouse ways and means sub-com\nmittee of crop surplus control leg\nislation which would increase the\ncurrent cost of farm legislation by\n$275,000,000 instead of reducing it,\nas Morgenthau said was necessary.\nInfluential southerners are break\ning away from the new deal on\nunemployment relief spending and\non wage and hours legislation. There\nis scattered legislative clamor from\nnorth and south for adjustment of\ntax inequities. A thorough-going\nrevision of the tax structure has\nbeen nromised for next winter.\nBusiness Recession Alarms\nThe administration is alarmed by\nbusiness recession and Mr. Roose\nvelt is conferring with industrialists\nin an effort to start a housing boom\nwhich would buoy business.\nCoincident with the sudden ad\nministration economy drive and the\nconvention of congress, the national\nconference of mayors, led by Mayor\nPiorello H. La Guardia of New\nYork, will meet here today. The\nmayors need federal money to\nlighten their municipal relief tax\nloads and to prevent uproar among\nthe unemployed. Their conference\nis being counted in advance among\nthe major obstacles to relief econ\nomy.\nSimilarly the pressure for ample\nfarm funds, highways subsidies and\ncontinued public works construction\ncombine to oppose speedy budget\nbalancinng. All these issues auto\nmatically go before this extraordin\nary session of congress. It is not\nbound in any way to restrict its\nconsideration to the legislation pro\nposed by Mr. Roosevelt.\nCrop Surplus Snagged\nCrop surplus control legislation is\nsnagged by dispute whether it shall\nbe voluntary or compulsory and\nover methods of financing the costly\nproject. It is estimated that surplus\ncontrol will cost 275,000,000 more\nthrn the existing $500.000,000-a\nyear soil conservation program,\nwhich it is designed to aosorb. A\nprecesslng tax on cotton or corn\nand other commodities affected is\nurged to raise the additional sum.\nMinimum wage and maximum\nhours legislation was before the first\nsession of the 75th congress but in\namke-shift form after legislators\nhaduhurriedly re-written the propo\nsal submitted by Mr. Roosevelt's\nadvLrors. The senate passed a bill\nbut the house blocked it as southern\nresentment arose against federal\nregulation of hours and wages on\n\u201cMY FRIENDS... WHO\u2019S WHO?\"\nm mm\nIf you thought you knew the features of President lMsndt H well\nyou'd recognise him on Main Street, see if you can piek out his jdctare\nabove. Unless you are an unusually keen observer of details, youTl nave\nas hard a time making the correct identification as strangers who en\ncounter the Roosevelt double, A. F. E. Rriggs, right, of Worcester, Mass,,\nfor the first time.\nWrecked Crew Had\nTo Fight For Lives\n(ConUnued fiom Pace 1)\nwhen the operator refused to do sc\nwithout the captains\u2019 order, drew\na knife and compelled him to send\nout the first call for assistance.\nSpeaking in Greek through C\nMoulis, Norfolk restaurant man whc\nacted as interpreter, the survivors\ntold a story of terror as the Tzenny\nChandrls finally went down under\nthe battering seas.\nCaptain Confopanoelis was at\ntacked by a seaman, they said, and\nwas bitten in the face before he\nwas able to beat the man off.\nHurled into the seas the men\nclung to life rafts and wreckage for\n32 hours before they were picked\nup. During the time they were\nbattered by the seas, they fought\noff sharks which attacked them\nagain and again.\nThe survivors were able to beat\noff the maneaters by kicking at\nthem, Joseph Corrie, an English\nsurvivor related. The sharks how\never, tore apart the bodies of the\nseamen who had been drowned.\nSurvivors Suffered\nAil of the survivors suffered from\nshock and exposure, and several had\nbeen badly bitten.\nOne of the 16 originally rescued\ndied en route here. The Mendota\nalso brought back tliree bodies tak\nen from the water.\nThe 15 survivors brought to 21\nthe known survivors of the crew of\n29. Six others were picked up by\nthe American tanker Swiftsure.\nThe freighters crew abandoned\nship after heavy seas flooded the\nengine rooms, disabling all machin\nery. With the boating listing 10\ndegrees, the captain, George Con\nfopanoells, sent an SOS and ordered\nthe crew overboard.\nThe men donned life belts and\nJumped\u2014their life boats had been\nwashed away. Ten minutes later the\nTzenny Chandris sank.\nGeorge Fotrnos, representative of\nthe Greek syndicate which owned\nthe Tzenny Chandris, was at the\npier. He was accompanied by Greek\ninterpreters to obtain, if possible,\ninformation from the men about\nthe disaster.\nLeaded With Scrap Metal\nThe freighter was en route from\nMorehead City, N. C., to Rotterdam\nWith a cargo of scrap metal when\nshe foundered 40 miles northeast of\nDiamond Shoals off Cape Hatteras\nin a 50-mile gale which swept the\nnortheast Atlantic coast.\nCoast guard cutters and planes\nand other vessels went to the crew\u2019s\nrescue.\nCoast guard cutters and planes\nand other vessels went to the crew\u2019s\nrescue.\nLieut. Richard Burke, pilot of a\ncoast guard amphibian plane, spot\nted the survivors in the water and\nsaw the sharks that threatened\ntheir lives. By dropping smoke\nbombs he directed the Mendota to\nRescuers experienced difficulty\nin obtaining details of the sinking\nof the freighter because the men\ncould speak practicaly no English,\nl ight Against Sharks\nLieut. Burke brought back a de\nscription of the seamen\u2019s fight\nagainst the attack of sharks. Upon\nhis return to the coast guard base\nhere last night he described to the\nUnited Press correspondent how the\nmen were rescued literally from the\njaws of the sharks.\n\u201cWe had been flying over the\nscene for about two hours when we\nsaw five dead bodies floating apout,\"\nBurke said. \u201cThen we saw two of\nscales which might deprive the\nsouth of its wage differential ad\nvantages over higher-paid north\nern areas.\nReorganization Plans\nReorganization of executive de\npartments as proposed by Mr.\nRoosevelt would enable him to con\nsolidate so-called independent agen-*\ncies, sucli as the interstate com\nmerce commission, with existing\ncabinet departments and shift var\nious bureaus from one to another\nof those departments. He also would\nhave had the power to abolish bu\nreaus and he asked congress to\ncreate two new cabinet departments,\npublic welfare and public works.\nThe bill would have created six\nnew eexcutives assistants for the\npresident, each with a \u201cpassion for\nanonymity.\u201d\nMr. Roosevelt is assured of his six\nnew assistants. Plans for a depart\nment of pjubllc work have been\nabandoned. A tremendous lobby\nwithin the government has devel\noped against ceding to Mr. Roosevelt\npower to shift bureaus from one\ndepartment to another, but he\nprobably will obtain limited author\nity in that direction.\nAnti-Trust Laws\nMr. Roosevelt's proposal for\namendment of anti-trust laws in\nbehalf of small business and in\nfurther prevention of monopoly was\nstated in vaguely general terms. It\nalready has been agreed among\ncongressional leaders that nothing\ncan be done on that until mid\nwinter.\nPlans for better use of land and\nwater resources involve the estab\nlishment of seven regional conser\nvation districts.\nTh^e authorities would deal pri\nmarily with flood control, power de\nvelopment, navigation and conserva\ntion of natural resources.\nthe crew. They were wearing\npreservers. One waved at us feebly\nThe other was bobbing up anc\ndown and kicking his feet.\n\"He seemed to have a lot of pep\nThen we were horrified to see shark!\nabout 15 feet away from these mer\nand headed straight for them. Th<\nman with all the pep seemed tc\nsense his danger and it looked to us\nlike he might be kicking at the\nsharks to try to keep them away\nSharks Everywhere\n\"Everywhere we looked there W\u2019ere\nsharks\u2014and more sharks. We im\nmediately dropped smoke bombs and\nzoomed about over the men to cal,\nattention of the coast guard cut\nter Mendota to their location. We\nalso hoped to frighten the sharks\nWe had about decided to take a\nchance and land in an attempt tc\nrescue the men when the Mendota\nput over a small boat and took them\naboard.\n\u201cIt was a horrible and gruesome\nsight. I don't know how many ol\nthe missing were eaten by sharks\nI didn\u2019t see anyone eaten but s\nnavy pilot who also flew over the\nscene told me that he saw shark!\ntearing apart bodies of the dead whe\nwere floating near the spot where\nthe ship went down.\n\"The boat must have carried some\nlive goats or sheep to be used as\nfood for the crew because we saw\ntheir carcasses floating and sharks\nnibbling at them.\nBurke said a high sea was run\nning and that debris of the wreck\nage was being tossed about by high\nwaves which made it hazardous tc\nland a plane.\n\u2018But we would have chanced it li\nthe Mendota hadn\u2019t reached the two\nsurvivors ahead of the sharks,\u201d he\nsaid.\n100 PEOPLE\nSHARE IN FUND\n(Continued trom Page 1)\nChristmas club deposits. Several\nbanks have met this situation with\na small service charge it was re\nported, but others are awaiting im\nproved money rates before attempt\ning the club savings plan.\nMoney for Shopping\nIt Is estimated thaht the vast sum,\nprimarily planned as Christmas\nshopping cash, will see at least 42\nper cent of the total going for that\npurpose. Another 26 per cent, is\nexpected to go Into permanent sav\nings, 12 per cent, for taxes, 8 per\ncent for mortgage Interest, 5 per\ncent for Insurance payments, 2 per\ncent for education, travel and char\nity.\nThe total estimated for New Eng\nland disbursement December 1, Is\n*40,b00,uuu, with Massachusetts\nChristmas club depositors getting\n628,100,000; Connecticut, second, *8,\n300,000; Rhode Island, third with *1,\n800,000; Maine, fourth, with *1.200,\n000; New Hampshire, fifth, with\n*900,000; and Vermont, sixth, with\n*500,000.\nCHEESE FROM GRASS PLANNED\nLondon (UP)\u2014A plan to \"short\ncircuit\u201d the cow and make cheese\ndirectly from grass to provide food\nfor Great Britain's population in\nevent of war was outlined to the\nBritish Association\u2019s meeting at\nNottingham.\nCENSUS PLAN ON\nUNEMPLOYMENT\n(Continued from Page 1)\nwhich hM been conducted for sev\neral weeks to Inform the nation of\nthe purposes and plans of the cen\nsus.\nTomorrow the post offlce depart\nment will distribute to every home\nthroughout the country approxi\nmately 40,000,000 questionnaire\ncards. Mr. Roosevelt asked all\ntotalling or partially unemployed\nworkers, \u201cwho are able to work, and\nwho are seeking work,\u201d to answer\nthe 14 questions on the cards and\nreturn them by mall to the govern\nment by Nov. 30. He said that this\nwould provide \"real facts upon\nwhich to base a sound re-employ\nment program.\u201d\nSimultaneously, the American\nFederation of Labor reported that\n\"the number without work Is still\nclose to 8,000,000\u201d and warned that\nunless the present wave of lay-offs\nis cheeked, It will result in \"the\nmost serious consequences.\u201d\nOutline of His Flans\nMr. Roosevelt revealed a general\noutline of how he plans to fit his\nprojected jobless aid scheme Into\nrecently stated budget-balancing ob\njectives. He Indicated that:\nl.The administration will retain\nIts pledge to prevent starvation\nthrough lack of aid, of any unem\nployed man or woman.\n3. the ultimate aim of the govern\nment will be to stimulate private\nindustry sufficiently to enable It to\nreabsorb the present core of un\nused man-power.\n3. A concrete plan for enabling\nthese concepts will be worked out\nas soon as possible after the results\nof tomorrow\u2019s tabulation have been\ncompleted.\nmay uaii in i<eaaers\nIt was reported that Mr. Roosevelt\nhas been advised to call a con\nference of Industrial and labor\nleaders as well as federal officials\nto map out a desirable program.\nJohn D. Biggers, Ohio glass man\nufacturer, Is supervising the census.\nThe president informed the nation\nIn his nation-wide broadcast that\nhe considered the projected census\n\u201can essential part of the greater\ntask of finding jobs for willing\nworkers who are Idle through no\nfault of their own.\u201d\n\u201cEnforced idleness, embracing any\nconsiderable portion of our people.\nIn a nation of such wealth and\nnatural opportunltty, is a paradox\nthat challenges our integrity,\u201d he\njsaid.\n\u201cThe permanent cure lies In find\ning suitable Jobs In Industry and\nagriculture for all willing workers.\nIt Involves co-operative effort and\nplanning which will lead to the ab\nsorption of this unused man-power\nIn private Industry....\"\nALLEGED NAZI\nCAMP ONLY NOISE\n(Continued from Page 1)\nout Waterbury for many years.\u201d\n\u201cI don\u2019t know of any Waterbury\npeople who have anything to do with\nthis camp,\u201d he stated. \u201cThe German\nAmericans here realize they have\nenough to do In trying to keep their\nown organizations going.\u201d\nHopes to Get Unit Here\nThe Bund hopes to organize units\nIn Waterury and other Connecticut\ncities. Represented now are six units,\nall from New York state. Yesterdaj\nsome 35 or 40 members were busy at\nthe tract, clearing away underbrush.\nThe Bund has been condemned by\nCongressman Samuel Dlcksteln, and\nby Jewish and anti-Nazi leaders\nabout the nation.\nSouthbury residents are said to be\nIndignant over the \u201cInvasion\u201d of\ntheir town, but had little comment\nto make. The camp Is said to be one\nof the largest Nazi camps in the\nnation.\nHIGHLIGHTS OF\nMESSAGE SENT IN\n(Continued from Page 1)\nalong the line* of modern business\nadministrative practice can in\ncrease efficiency, minimise error,\nduplication and waste, and raise\nthe morale of the public service.\u201d\n\"To avoid waste and to give the\nnation its money\u2019s worth from the\nnational funds we expend, we\nmust, like any business corpora\ntion, have a definite building and\noperating plan worked out ahead\nof time\u2014a planned order In which\nto make expenditures, a planned\ntiming for expenditures so that we\nmay keep our working force em\nployed, and a planned coordinated\nuse of the projects after comple\ntion.\u201d\nWhat Do You Know About Health? i\nBy FISHER BROWN \u00abnd NAT FALK\nBWIHUJI ni>\u2014hialth HPUividi iflg\"1\"\"1\"\ni Who was\nAlHAZEN?\nDo KOPte\nHAVE 1\u00a9\nPShSPtftB I\n\nrK ;X.2L\nI.WhAT no THS WOMEN OP\nAnswers:\n1. Stmitlmii\ncalled \"The Duett\nScientist,\u201d Alhazan is the most fam\nous of the Arabian opticians who\nmade important contributions to tha\nscience of optics. Alhazen\u2019s treatise\ngave the first comprehensive survey\nof this science. He is particularly\nfor his\nof UaU\n2. Yet. Perspiration is a basic\n(actor of normal physical life. The\nchief function of perspiration is haat\nregulation of the body. A person\ncannot live if the body surface is\nburned ao badly as to destroy the\ngreater portion of the sweat glands.\n3, Broad crumbs dissolved in milk.\nThis propomtion was ran si tier ad a\n__\nDay Labor Irks,\nSays Ickes\u2019 Son\nA Job totin\u2019 (tool with a Youngs\ntown, O., engineering Arm is not\nexactly to the llkng of Robert\nH. Ickes, foster son of the sec\nretary of interior, he admitted\nwhen pictured above after long\nhours as a day laborer. oYung\nIckes wants to be a newspaper\nman, dislikes polttcs. He also has\ntried PWA work, as clerk on a\nsewer construction job.\nNEW ARMY TO\nJOIN CHINESE\n(Continued irom Page 1)\nbe spilt Into guerrilla units and de\ntailed to harass the Japanese along\ntheir extremely extended line of\ncommunication back to Kalgan.\nThe Chinese, abandoning Taiyuan\nin face of a Japanese advance In\nforce, have removed their headquar\nters to this city of Fengyang, 65\nmiles southwest of Taiyuan.\nThe 8th route army, the former\nChinese communist army, has been\nwithdrawn from the north to ap\nproach nearer to the men of the\ncentral government arms, and these\nmen, too, are expected to Join in a\nguerrilla campaign.\nBy JOHN R. MORRS\n(United Press Staff Correspondent)\nShanghai, Nov. 16\u2014(UP)\u2014Japa\nnese authorities may offer peace\nterms to China after they reach\nSoochow, 45 miles west of Shanghai,\nit was reported today.\nChinese defense eastward of J\nSoochow seemed crumbling, and a\nJapanese spokesman announced the\ncapture of Quinsan, only 15 miles\neast of that city on which the Chi\nnese defense line is to be based.\nThe spokesman claimed advances\non all sectors, including the extreme\nnorthern part of the front where,\nhe said, Japanese reinforcements\nhad landed on the south bank of\nthe Yangtze river and attacked 1\nChanghsu, 20 miles north of Soo- 1\nchow.\nThus three Japanese armies were\ndriving toward the Soochow line,\nas a third force is advancing\nnorthward and westward from\nHangchow bay.\nSome Speculation\nThere was specuiation on the ex\ntent to which th eJapanese would 1\nseek to penetrate inland\u2014particu\nlarly whether they would make an\neffort to go as far as Nanking, the\nnational capital, which is 235 miles\nfrom the coast.\nit was reported tnat oen. iwane\nHatsul, Japanese commander In\nchief, might oiler peace terms as\nsoon os the Japanese reached Soo-\nchow and then, 11 the terms were\nrejected, essay the Nanking cam- i\npalgn. The Nanking march would\nbe a threat over China's head.\nFor the present the Chinese were\nretreating rapidly and oflerlng al\nmost no resistance. They asserted\nthat they wgere merely retiring to\nthe new Soochow line and would\nmake their next stand there.\nIn token that they have their t\nminds on Nanking, the Japanese f\nsent an airplane fleet to boipb the v\ncapital again today. Nine planes\nbombed the Nanking arsenal and c\nmilitary airdrome.\nHere the situation was quiet but\nthere were signs of increased Japa-\nnese determination to dominate the\ncity.\nSoochow Bombarded\nShanghai, Nov. 15\u2014 (UP)\u2014 A ter- r\nrifle bombardment of Soochow, 45 c\nnese airplanes, was reported from l\nmiles west of Shanghai, by Japa- t\nNanking today. f\nThe reports said more than 700\nbombs had been dropped In the past\n30 hours as the Japanese sought to\nsmash the defense line.\nCHINA\u2019S PLAN\nTO BLOCK JAPAN\n(Continued from Page 1)\ngree her shipping to provide out\nlets for her expanding Industries\nand to And means of payment for\nher foreign purchases.\n\u201cRefusal* to admit all or certain\nof her exports and to make use of\nher shipping will have the effect not\nonly of disorganizing her Industry\nbut also of depriving her of the\nmeans of obtaining the necessary\nforeign credit.\nJapan Paying Plenty\n\u201cSince It Is a well known fact\nthat Japan\u2019s present campaigns In\nChina involve a heavy drain on her\nfinancial resources and that by the\nend of the present year the Japa\nnese diet will again be called upon\nto vote further large appropriations\nto cover the cost of military ad\nventures, to deny her any opportu\nnity of obtaining a foreign loan or\notherwise procuring credit from for\neign sources, will render the eco\nnomic measures Indicated more er\nfetive.\"\nRetarding extension of aid to\nGrieve, Bisset Holland, fo\n\"Waterbury's Dependable Store\"\nOur Biggest 3c Sale of Notions, Novelties and\nChristmas Tree Ornaments and Decorations will\nbegin TUESDAY and last all this week\u2014\nthrough Saturday. A large assortment of useful\nand ornamental articles to choose from!\nCome and See What 3c\nWill Buy\nHere Are a Few of the Many Items!\nTomato Pin Cushions\nMending Thread Sets\nWood Mixing Spoons\nSewing Boxes\nDish Cloths\nMetal Pot Cleaners\nBias T